In this example, we add a media query that targets screens with a maximum width of 600px. We adjust the height of the container and the width, padding, and margin of the child divs to make the design more suitable for smaller screens.

**Split and Fill Vertical HTML Divs**

Here is an example of how you can split and fill vertical HTML divs using CSS:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta http-equiv="X-UA-Compatible" content="IE=edge">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Split and Fill Vertical Divs</title>
    <style>
        /* Style for container */
       .container {
            width: 400px;
            margin: 20px auto;
            display: flex;
            flex-direction: column;
            align-items: stretch;
        }

        /* Style for child divs */
       .child {
            width: 100%;
            height: 100px;
            background-color: #ccc;
            margin-bottom: 10px;
        }

        /* Style for stretch child div */
       .stretch-child {
            flex-grow: 1;
            background-color: #f0f0f0;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div class="container">
        <div class="child">Div 1</div>
        <div class="stretch-child">This is a stretch child div. It will take up any extra space.</div>
        <div class="child">Div 2</div>
        <div class="child">Div 3</div>
    </div>
</body>
</html>
```

**How it works:**

* We create a container div with `flex-direction: column` to stack its children vertically.
* We use `align-items: stretch` to make the children divs take up the full width of the container.
* We style the child divs with `width: 100%` and `height: 100px` to make them responsive.
* We add a `margin-bottom` to separate the divs.
* We create a stretch child div with `flex-grow: 1` to make it take up any extra space.

**Tips and Variations:**

* To make the stretch child div take up only a certain amount of space, you can use `flex-basis` instead of `flex-grow`.
* To add a maximum height to the stretch child div, you can use `max-height` in the CSS.
* To use a different layout for the container, you can use `display: grid` or `display: block` instead of `display: flex`.

